data.title: N.K. leader celebrates completion of 10,000 new homes in Pyongyang

data.text:
SEOUL, April 17 (Yonhap) -- North Korean leader Kim Jong-un has attended a ceremony marking the completion of building another 10,000 new homes in Pyongyang, state media said Wednesday.

Kim attended the ribbon-cutting ceremony Tuesday for the completion of new apartments in the Hwasong district of Pyongyang as part of a housing project to build a combined 50,000 new homes in the capital by 2025, the Korean Central News Agency (KCNA) said.

Kim called for workers to attain the remaining goals for the five-year project to "turn the capital Pyongyang into a world-famous civilized city fit for might of a powerful Korea in name and reality," according to the KCNA.

Kim has pushed for the project in apparent efforts to achieve economic feats and improve people's livelihoods in the face of economic hardships stemming from U.N sanctions.

North Korea has been under tightened U.N. sanctions due to its nuclear and missile programs, which call for, among other things, a ban on the country's exports of coal and other mineral resources to cut off North Korea's access to hard currency.

With the latest completion, North Korea has so far supplied 30,000 new homes in the Hwasong and Songhwa districts of Pyongyang since unveiling the project in a 2021 party meeting.
